.sp
.block 5
.center
A LISP Interpreter
.sp
	Here is one possible
interpreter for the LISP dialect we have described,
written in that dialect (this fact makes this interpreter meta-circular 4~*
it can interpret itself):
.sp
.nofill
.spw 13
.block 14
1     (DEFINE EVAL
	     (LAMBDA (EXP ENV)
		     (IF (ATOM EXP)
			 (IF (NUMBERP EXP) EXP (VALUE EXP ENV))
			 (IF (EQ (CAR EXP) 'QUOTE)
			     (CADR EXP)
			     (IF (EQ (CAR EXP) 'LAMBDA)
				 (LIST '&PROCEDURE (CADR EXP) (CADDR EXP) ENV)
				 (IF (EQ (CAR EXP) 'IF)
				     (IF (EVAL (CADR EXP) ENV)
					 (EVAL (CADDR EXP) ENV)
					 (EVAL (CADDDR EXP) ENV))
				     (APPLY (EVAL (CAR EXP) ENV)
					    (EVLIS (CDR EXP) ENV))))))))
.spw 16
.adjust
.sp
0

.nofill
.spw 13
.block 7
1     (DEFINE APPLY
	     (LAMBDA (FUN ARGS)
		     (IF (PRIMOP FUN) (PRIMOP-APPLY FUN ARGS)
			 (IF (EQ (CAR FUN) '&PROCEDURE)
			     (EVAL (CADDR FUN)
				   (BIND (CADR FUN) ARGS (CADDDR FUN)))
			     (ERROR)))))
.spw 16
.adjust
.sp
0

.nofill
.spw 13
.block 5
1     (DEFINE EVLIS
	     (LAMBDA (ARGLIST ENV)
		     (IF (NULL ARGLIST) '()
			 (CONS (EVAL (CAR ARGLIST) ENV)
			       (EVLIS (CDR ARGLIST) ENV)))))
.spw 16
.adjust
.sp
0
	The evaluator
is divided into two conceptual components: 1EVAL* and 1APPLY*.
1EVAL* classifies expressions and directs their evaluation.
Simple expressions (such as constants and variables) can be evaluated directly.
For the complex case of procedure invocations (technically called
"combinations"), 1EVAL* looks up the procedure definition,
recursively evaluates the arguments (using 1EVLIS*), and then calls
1APPLY*.
1APPLY* classifies procedures and directs their application.
Simple procedures (primitive operators) are applied directly.
For the complex case of user-defined procedures, 1APPLY*
uses 1BIND* (see below) to add to the lexical environment, a kind of symbol table,
of the procedure,
by associating the formal parameters from the procedure definition
with the actual argument values provided by 1EVAL*.
The body of the procedure definition is then passed to 1EVAL*,
along with the environment just constructed, which is used to
determine the values of variables occurring in the body.
.sp
	In more detail, 1EVAL* is a case analysis on the
structure of the S-expression 1EXP*.
If it is an atom, there are two subcases.
Numeric atoms evaluate to themselves.
Atomic symbols, however, encode variables; the value associated
with that symbol is extracted from the environment 1ENV* using
the function 1VALUE* (see below).
.sp
	If the expression to be evaluated is not atomic,
then it may be a 1QUOTE* form, a 1LAMBDA* form, an 1IF* form, or a combination.
For a 1QUOTE* form, 1EVAL* extracts the S-expression constant
using 1CADR*.  1LAMBDA* forms evaluate to procedure objects
(here represented as lists whose cars are the atom "1&PROCEDURE*")
containing the lexical environment and the "text" of the procedure definition.
For an 1IF* form, the predicate part is recursively evaluated;
depending on whether the result is true or false, the consequent
or alternative is selected for evaluation.
For combinations, the procedure is obtained, the arguments
evaluated (using 1EVLIS*), and 1APPLY* called as described earlier.
.sp
	1EVLIS* is a simple recursive function which calls 1EVAL*
on successive arguments in 1ARGLIST* and produces a list
of the values in order.
.sp
	1APPLY* distinguishes two kinds of procedures:
primitive and user-defined.  For now we avoid describing the
precise implementation of primitive procedures by assuming the
existence of a predicate 1PRIMOP* which is true only of
primitive procedures, and a function 1PRIMOP-APPLY*
which deals with the application of such primitive procedures.
We consider primitive procedures
to be a kind of atomic S-expression other than numbers and
atomic symbols; we define no particular written notation for them here.
However, primitive procedures are not to be confused with the atomic
symbols used as their names.  The actual procedure involved in the
combination 1(CAR_X)*
is not the atomic symbol 1CAR*, but rather some bizarre object
(the value of the atomic symbol 1CAR*)
which is meaningful only to 1PRIMOP-APPLY*.
.sp
	The interpreter uses several utility procedures
for maintaining environments.
An environment is represented as a list of buckets;
each bucket is a list whose car is a list of names
and whose cdr is a list of corresponding values.
(Note that this representation is not the same as the "a-list"
representation traditionally used in LISP interpreters.)
If a variable name occurs in more than one bucket,
the most recently added such bucket has priority; in this way
new symbol definitions added to the front of the list
can supersede old ones.  The code for manipulating environments is below.
.sp
.nofill
